129
00:11:46,740 --> 00:11:47,420


130
00:11:47,540 --> 00:11:48,860


131
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:57,120
Two trips around the world this month.

132
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:59,180
You didn't ask his secretary,

133
00:11:59,180 --> 00:12:01,240
you said that just to irritate him.

134
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:03,080
- How did you know? - Did you see his watch?

135
00:12:03,080 --> 00:12:04,840
His watch?

136
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:06,160
The time was right, but the date was wrong.

137
00:12:06,160 --> 00:12:09,920
Said two days ago. Crossed the date line twice and he didn't alter it.

138
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:12,160
- Within a month? How did you get that? - New Breitling.

139
00:12:12,160 --> 00:12:13,600
Only came out this February.

140
00:12:14,680 --> 00:12:18,320
OK. So do you think we should sniff around here for a bit longer?

141
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:20,320
Got everything I need to know already, thanks.

142
00:12:20,320 --> 00:12:21,560
That graffiti was a message.

143
00:12:22,740 --> 00:12:24,420
Someone at the bank, working on the trading floors.

144
00:12:24,420 --> 00:12:27,060
We find the intended recipient and...

145
00:12:27,060 --> 00:12:29,060
They'll lead us to the person who sent it?

146
00:12:29,060 --> 00:12:30,060
Obvious.

147
00:12:30,060 --> 00:12:32,180
Well, there's 300 people up there, who was it meant for?

148
00:12:32,180 --> 00:12:34,700
- Pillars. - What?

149
00:12:34,700 --> 00:12:35,780
Pillars and the screens.

150
00:12:35,780 --> 00:12:37,580
Very few places you could see that graffiti from.

151
00:12:37,580 --> 00:12:39,270
That narrows the field considerably.

152
00:12:39,270 --> 00:12:42,180
And, of course, the message was left at 11:34 last night.

153
00:12:42,180 --> 00:12:43,300
That tells us a lot.

154
00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:45,140
- Does it? - Traders come to work at all hours.

155
00:12:45,140 --> 00:12:46,900
Some trade with Hong Kong in the middle of the night.

156
00:12:45,540 --> 00:12:47,220


157
00:12:46,900 --> 00:12:51,260
That message was intended for somebody who came in at midnight.

158
00:12:51,260 --> 00:12:54,020
Not many Van Coons in the phone book.

159
00:12:51,660 --> 00:12:52,300


160
00:12:54,020 --> 00:12:55,060
Taxi!

161
00:13:04,940 --> 00:13:05,820


162
00:13:15,860 --> 00:13:18,900
So what do we do now? Sit here and wait for him to come back?

163
00:13:18,900 --> 00:13:20,860
- Just moved in. - What?

164
00:13:20,860 --> 00:13:24,140
- Floor above, new label. - Could have just replaced it.

165
00:13:22,620 --> 00:13:26,460


166
00:13:26,140 --> 00:13:28,130
No-one ever does that.

167
00:13:28,130 --> 00:13:29,260
Hello?

168
00:13:29,260 --> 00:13:33,940
Hi, um, I live in the flat just below you. I don't think we've met.

169
00:13:33,940 --> 00:13:36,540
No, well, er, I've just moved in.

170
00:13:37,780 --> 00:13:41,700
Actually, I've just locked my keys in my flat.

171
00:13:41,700 --> 00:13:43,100
Do you want me to buzz you in?

172
00:13:43,100 --> 00:13:45,620
Yeah. And can we use your balcony?

173
00:13:45,620 --> 00:13:46,740
What?!

174
00:14:26,020 --> 00:14:29,100
Sherlock?

175
00:14:29,100 --> 00:14:31,060
Sherlock, are you OK?

176
00:14:36,780 --> 00:14:39,220
Yeah, any time you feel like letting me in!

177
00:14:53,500 --> 00:14:55,660
Do you think he'd lost a lot of money?

178
00:14:55,660 --> 00:14:57,860
Suicide is pretty common among City boys.

179
00:14:57,860 --> 00:14:59,900
- We don't know that it was suicide. - Come on.

180
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:03,020
The door was locked from the inside, you had to climb down the balcony.

181
00:15:03,020 --> 00:15:07,140
Been away three days judging by the laundry.

182
00:15:09,180 --> 00:15:11,460
Look at the case, there was something tightly packed inside it.

183
00:15:11,460 --> 00:15:14,300
- Thanks. I'll take your word for it. - Problem?

184
00:15:14,300 --> 00:15:17,940
Yeah, I'm not desperate to root around some bloke's dirty underwear.

185
00:15:17,940 --> 00:15:21,500
Those symbols at the bank, the graffiti, why were they put there?

186
00:15:21,500 --> 00:15:23,580
- Some sort of code? - Obviously.

187
00:15:23,580 --> 00:15:25,980
Why were they painted? Want to communicate, why not use e-mail?

188
00:15:25,980 --> 00:15:27,580
Well, maybe he wasn't answering.

189
00:15:27,580 --> 00:15:29,100
Oh, good, you follow.

190
00:15:29,100 --> 00:15:30,940
No.

191
00:15:30,940 --> 00:15:33,540
What kind of a message would everyone try to avoid?

192
00:15:35,100 --> 00:15:36,580
What about this morning?

193
00:15:36,580 --> 00:15:40,060
- Those letters you were looking at? - Bills?

194
00:15:42,020 --> 00:15:45,140
Yes. He was being threatened.

195
00:15:46,700 --> 00:15:47,780
Not by the Gas Board.

196
00:15:47,780 --> 00:15:50,580
...see if we can get prints off this glass.

197
00:15:50,580 --> 00:15:52,540
Sergeant, we haven't met.

198
00:15:52,540 --> 00:15:53,860
Yeah, I know who you are

199
00:15:53,860 --> 00:15:56,260
and I would prefer it if you didn't tamper with any of the evidence.

200
00:16:00,620 --> 00:16:03,550
I phoned Lestrade. Is he on his way?

201
00:16:03,550 --> 00:16:05,020
He's busy. I'm in charge.

202
00:16:05,020 --> 00:16:08,860
And it's not Sergeant, it's Detective Inspector Dimmock.

203
00:16:12,700 --> 00:16:14,500
We're obviously looking at a suicide.

204
00:16:14,500 --> 00:16:17,100
It does seem the only explanation of all the facts.

205
00:16:17,100 --> 00:16:19,620
Wrong, it's one possible explanation of some of the facts.

206
00:16:19,620 --> 00:16:22,020
You've got a solution that you like, but you are choosing

207
00:16:22,020 --> 00:16:24,060
to ignore anything you see that doesn't comply with it.

208
00:16:24,060 --> 00:16:25,980
- Like? - Wound's on the right side of his head.

209
00:16:25,980 --> 00:16:27,260
- And? - Van Coon was left-handed.

210
00:16:27,260 --> 00:16:29,700
Requires quite a bit of contortion.

211
00:16:29,700 --> 00:16:32,120
- Left-handed? - I'm amazed you didn't notice.

212
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:33,340
All you have to do is look around this flat.

213
00:16:33,340 --> 00:16:35,260
Coffee table on the left-hand side,

214
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:36,900
coffee mug handle pointing to the left.

215
00:16:36,900 --> 00:16:38,850
Power sockets, habitually used the ones on the left.

216
00:16:38,860 --> 00:16:40,410
Pen and paper on the left of the phone.

217
00:16:40,420 --> 00:16:42,660
Because he picked up with his right, took messages with his left.

218
00:16:42,660 --> 00:16:44,460
- D'you want me to go on? - No, I think you've covered it.

219
00:16:44,460 --> 00:16:46,220
I might as well, I'm almost at the bottom of the list.

220
00:16:46,220 --> 00:16:48,940
There's a knife on the breadboard with butter on the right side of the blade

221
00:16:48,940 --> 00:16:50,020
because he used it with his left.

222
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:50,660
It's highly unlikely

223
00:16:50,660 --> 00:16:52,900
that a left-handed man would shoot himself in the right of his head.

224
00:16:52,900 --> 00:16:55,060
Conclusion, someone broke in here and murdered him -

225
00:16:55,060 --> 00:16:56,980
only explanation of all of the facts.

226
00:16:56,980 --> 00:16:59,060
- But the gun? - He was waiting for the killer.

227
00:16:59,060 --> 00:17:01,900
- He'd been threatened. - What?

228
00:17:01,900 --> 00:17:04,780
Today at the bank, sort of a warning.

229
00:17:04,780 --> 00:17:06,820
He fired a shot when his attacker came in.

230
00:17:06,820 --> 00:17:09,340
- And the bullet? - Went through the open window.

231
00:17:09,340 --> 00:17:11,260
Oh, come on!

232
00:17:11,260 --> 00:17:13,020
What are the chances of that?!

233
00:17:13,020 --> 00:17:15,260
Wait until you get the ballistics report.

234
00:17:15,260 --> 00:17:18,060
The bullet in his brain wasn't fired from his gun, I guarantee it.

235
00:17:18,060 --> 00:17:22,300
If his door was locked from the inside, how did the killer get in?

236
00:17:22,300 --> 00:17:25,180
Good, you're finally asking the right questions.

237
00:17:31,820 --> 00:17:34,500
He's left trying to sort of cut his hair with a fork,

238
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:36,300
which of course can never be done.

239
00:17:36,300 --> 00:17:39,180
It was a threat, that's what the graffiti meant.

240
00:17:39,180 --> 00:17:40,340
I'm kind of in a meeting.

241
00:17:40,340 --> 00:17:42,700
Can you make an appointment with my secretary?

242
00:17:42,700 --> 00:17:45,940
I don't think this can wait. Sorry, Sebastian.

243
00:17:45,940 --> 00:17:49,940
One of your traders, someone who worked in your office, was killed.

244
00:17:49,940 --> 00:17:51,740
- What? - Van Coon.

245
00:17:51,740 --> 00:17:52,820
The police are at his flat.

246
00:17:52,820 --> 00:17:56,070
- Killed?! - Sorry to interfere with everyone's digestion.

247
00:17:56,070 --> 00:17:57,900
Still want to make an appointment?

248
00:17:57,900 --> 00:18:00,180
Would maybe nine o'clock at Scotland Yard suit?

249
00:18:04,380 --> 00:18:08,060
Harrow, Oxford...very bright guy.

250
00:18:09,620 --> 00:18:12,100
Worked in Asia for a while, so...

251
00:18:12,100 --> 00:18:13,780
You gave him the Hong Kong accounts?

252
00:18:15,780 --> 00:18:20,020
Lost 5 million in a single morning, made it all back a week later.

253
00:18:20,020 --> 00:18:21,620
Nerves of steel, Eddie had.

254
00:18:21,620 --> 00:18:24,020
- Who'd want to kill him? - We all make enemies.

255
00:18:24,020 --> 00:18:25,780
You don't all end up with a bullet through your temple.

256
00:18:25,780 --> 00:18:28,220
Not usually. Excuse me.

257
00:18:31,260 --> 00:18:33,460
It's my chairman.

258
00:18:33,460 --> 00:18:35,340
Police have been on to him.

259
00:18:35,340 --> 00:18:38,010
Apparently they're telling him it was a suicide.

260
00:18:38,010 --> 00:18:40,340
Well, they've got it wrong, Sebastian. He was murdered.

261
00:18:40,340 --> 00:18:43,220
Well, I'm afraid they don't see it like that.

262
00:18:43,220 --> 00:18:45,460
- So? - And neither does my boss.

263
00:18:45,460 --> 00:18:48,660
I hired you to do a job. Don't get sidetracked.

264
00:18:52,140 --> 00:18:54,580
I thought bankers were all supposed to be heartless bastards.

265
00:19:42,700 --> 00:19:45,580
I need you to get over to Crispians.

266
00:19:45,580 --> 00:19:49,700
Two Ming vases up for auction - Chenghua.

267
00:19:49,700 --> 00:19:51,410
Will you appraise them?

268
00:19:51,410 --> 00:19:53,900
Soo Lin should go. She's the expert.

269
00:19:53,900 --> 00:19:56,500
Soo Lin has resigned her job. I need you.

270
00:20:06,580 --> 00:20:08,140


271
00:20:45,860 --> 00:20:46,820


272
00:20:50,140 --> 00:20:52,900
- Just locum work. - No, that's fine.

273
00:20:54,460 --> 00:20:57,100
You're, um... well, you're a bit over-qualified.

274
00:20:58,940 --> 00:21:01,180
Er, I could always do with the money.

275
00:21:01,180 --> 00:21:04,700
Well, we've got two away on holiday this week

276
00:21:04,700 --> 00:21:07,180
and one's just left to have a baby.

277
00:21:07,180 --> 00:21:09,940
It might be a bit mundane for you.

278
00:21:09,940 --> 00:21:13,740
Er, no, mundane is good, sometimes.

279
00:21:13,740 --> 00:21:15,340
Mundane works.

280
00:21:15,340 --> 00:21:19,540
- It says here you were a soldier. - And a doctor.

281
00:21:21,700 --> 00:21:23,940
Anything else you can do?

282
00:21:23,940 --> 00:21:25,980
I learned the clarinet at school.

283
00:21:25,980 --> 00:21:30,620
Oh..well, I'll look forward to it.

284
00:21:37,940 --> 00:21:40,380
I said, could you pass me a pen?

285
00:21:41,940 --> 00:21:43,780
- What? When? - About an hour ago.

286
00:21:45,340 --> 00:21:47,700
Didn't notice I'd gone out then?

287
00:21:49,260 --> 00:21:51,740
I went to see about a job at that surgery.

288
00:21:51,740 --> 00:21:54,660
- How was it? - Great. She's great.

289
00:21:54,660 --> 00:21:56,620
Who?

290
00:21:56,620 --> 00:21:57,900
The job.

291
00:21:57,900 --> 00:21:58,980
She?!

292
00:22:00,140 --> 00:22:01,100
It.

293
00:22:03,220 --> 00:22:04,420
Yeah, have a look.

294
00:22:10,980 --> 00:22:12,940
"The intruder who can walk through walls."

295
00:22:12,940 --> 00:22:14,070
It happened last night.

296
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:16,070
Journalist shot dead in his flat.

297
00:22:16,790 --> 00:22:18,440
Doors locked, windows bolted from the inside.

298
00:22:18,440 --> 00:22:21,180
Exactly the same as Van Coon.

299
00:22:21,380 --> 00:22:25,220
- God! You think...? - He's killed another one.

300
00:22:29,500 --> 00:22:32,460


301
00:22:33,110 --> 00:22:36,270
Brian Lukis, freelance journalist,

302
00:22:36,270 --> 00:22:38,580
murdered in his flat.

303
00:22:38,580 --> 00:22:40,790
Doors locked from the inside.

304
00:22:40,790 --> 00:22:42,630
You've got to admit, it's similar.

305
00:22:42,630 --> 00:22:44,290
Both men killed by someone

306
00:22:44,300 --> 00:22:46,670
who can walk through solid walls.

307
00:22:46,670 --> 00:22:48,220
Inspector, do you seriously believe

308
00:22:48,220 --> 00:22:50,550
that Eddie Van Coon was just another city suicide?

309
00:22:53,200 --> 00:22:55,590
You have seen the ballistics report, I suppose?

310
00:22:56,560 --> 00:22:58,930
And the shot that killed him was it fired from his own gun?

311
00:22:58,930 --> 00:23:01,940
- No. - No. So this investigation might move a bit quicker

312
00:23:01,940 --> 00:23:04,070
if you were to take my word as gospel.

313
00:23:06,340 --> 00:23:08,640
I've just handed you a murder inquiry.

314
00:23:09,660 --> 00:23:12,780
Five minutes in his flat.

315
00:23:39,890 --> 00:23:41,360
Four floors up.

316
00:23:42,170 --> 00:23:43,770
That's why they think they're safe.

317
00:23:45,020 --> 00:23:46,020
Put a chain across the door,

318
00:23:46,020 --> 00:23:48,820
bolt it shut, think they're impregnable.

319
00:23:50,380 --> 00:23:54,780
They don't reckon for one second that there's another way in.

320
00:23:54,780 --> 00:23:56,660
- I don't understand. - Dealing with a killer who can climb.

321
00:23:58,440 --> 00:24:00,130
What are you doing?

322
00:24:00,130 --> 00:24:02,250
Clings to the walls like an insect.

323
00:24:02,940 --> 00:24:04,090
That's how he got in.

324
00:24:04,090 --> 00:24:05,210
What?!

325
00:24:05,210 --> 00:24:08,410
He climbed up the side of the walls, ran along the roof,

326
00:24:08,410 --> 00:24:10,050
dropped in through this skylight.

327
00:24:10,050 --> 00:24:12,180
You're not serious?! Like Spider-Man?

328
00:24:12,180 --> 00:24:15,250
He scaled six floors of a Docklands apartment building,

329
00:24:15,250 --> 00:24:16,420
jumped the balcony and killed Van Coon.

330
00:24:16,420 --> 00:24:17,850
Oh, hold on!

331
00:24:17,850 --> 00:24:19,350
And of course that's how he got into the bank -

332
00:24:19,350 --> 00:24:21,440
He ran along the window ledge onto the terrace.

333
00:24:23,660 --> 00:24:26,940
I have to find out what connects these two men.

334
00:24:32,810 --> 00:24:34,460


335
00:24:54,430 --> 00:24:57,400
Date stamped on the book is the same day that he died.

336
00:25:06,700 --> 00:25:08,420
Sherlock?

337
00:25:19,280 --> 00:25:20,410
So, the killer goes to the bank,

338
00:25:20,410 --> 00:25:22,220
leaves a threatening cipher for Van Coon.

339
00:25:22,220 --> 00:25:25,310
Van Coon panics, returns to his apartment, locks himself in.

340
00:25:25,310 --> 00:25:27,100
Hours later, he dies.

341
00:25:27,550 --> 00:25:30,050
The killer finds Lukis at the library,

342
00:25:30,050 --> 00:25:33,220
he writes the cipher on the shelf where he knows it'll be seen.

343
00:25:33,220 --> 00:25:34,800
Lukis goes home.

344
00:25:34,800 --> 00:25:36,950
Late that night, he dies too.

345
00:25:39,940 --> 00:25:41,290
Why did they die, Sherlock?

346
00:25:42,180 --> 00:25:43,680
Only the cipher can tell us.

347
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:52,200
The world's run on codes and ciphers, John.

348
00:25:52,880 --> 00:25:54,890
From the million-pound security system at the bank

349
00:25:54,890 --> 00:25:56,700
to the PIN machine you took exception to.

350
00:25:56,700 --> 00:25:58,670
Cryptography inhabits our every waking moment.

351
00:25:58,670 --> 00:25:59,850
Yes, OK, but...

352
00:25:59,850 --> 00:26:02,040
But it's all computer generated

353
00:26:02,040 --> 00:26:04,090
electronic codes, electronic ciphering methods.

354
00:26:05,150 --> 00:26:06,280
This is different.

355
00:26:06,280 --> 00:26:08,430
It's an ancient device.

356
00:26:08,430 --> 00:26:10,640
Modern code-breaking methods won't unravel it.

357
00:26:10,640 --> 00:26:12,650
- Where are we headed? - I need to ask some advice.

358
00:26:12,650 --> 00:26:15,250
What?! Sorry?

359
00:26:16,410 --> 00:26:18,500
You heard me perfectly. I'm not saying it again.

360
00:26:18,500 --> 00:26:20,170
- You need advice? - On painting.

361
00:26:20,170 --> 00:26:22,030
Yes, I need to talk to an expert.

362
00:26:31,210 --> 00:26:32,760
Part of a new exhibition.

363
00:26:33,740 --> 00:26:35,640
- Interesting. - I call it...

364
00:26:36,670 --> 00:26:38,860
Urban Bloodlust Frenzy.

365
00:26:39,180 --> 00:26:40,490
Catchy!

366
00:26:41,210 --> 00:26:43,560
I've got two minutes before a Community Support Officer

367
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:44,980
comes around that corner.

368
00:26:45,830 --> 00:26:47,650
Can we do this while I'm working?

369
00:26:53,170 --> 00:26:54,940
Know the author?

370
00:26:54,940 --> 00:26:56,310
I recognise the paint.

371
00:26:57,010 --> 00:26:59,360
It's like Michigan...hard-core propellant.

372
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:01,020
I'd say zinc.

373
00:27:01,020 --> 00:27:03,140
And what about the symbols? Do you recognise them?

374
00:27:04,400 --> 00:27:06,110
I'm not even sure it's a proper language.

375
00:27:06,800 --> 00:27:08,530
Two men have been murdered, Raz.

376
00:27:08,530 --> 00:27:10,820
Deciphering this is the key to finding out who killed them.

377
00:27:11,900 --> 00:27:13,190
And this is all you've got to go on?

378
00:27:14,210 --> 00:27:16,760
- It's hardly much, is it? - Are you going to help us or not?

379
00:27:18,350 --> 00:27:19,280
I'll ask around.

380
00:27:19,280 --> 00:27:22,310
Somebody must know something about it.

381
00:27:24,880 --> 00:27:26,090
What the hell do you think you're doing?

382
00:27:26,090 --> 00:27:28,000
This gallery is a listed public building.

383
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:29,800
No, no. Wait, wait. It's not me who painted that.

384
00:27:29,800 --> 00:27:31,120
I was just holding this for...

385
00:27:37,690 --> 00:27:39,130
Bit of an enthusiast, are we?

386
00:27:42,890 --> 00:27:46,160
She was right in the middle of an important piece of restoration.

387
00:27:46,160 --> 00:27:47,990
Why would she suddenly resign?

388
00:27:47,990 --> 00:27:50,150
Family problems. She said so in her letter.

389
00:27:50,150 --> 00:27:51,280
But she doesn't have a family.

390
00:27:51,280 --> 00:27:53,030
She came to this country on her own.

391
00:27:53,030 --> 00:27:55,820
- Andy! - Look, those teapots, those ceramics.

392
00:27:55,820 --> 00:27:57,220
They've become her obsession.

393
00:27:57,220 --> 00:27:59,800
She's been working on restoring them for weeks.

394
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:02,820
I can't believe that she would just...abandon them.

395
00:28:03,810 --> 00:28:06,880
Perhaps she was getting a bit of unwanted attention?

396
00:28:19,180 --> 00:28:20,470
You've been a while.

397
00:28:22,950 --> 00:28:24,310
Yeah, well, you know how it is.

398
00:28:24,310 --> 00:28:27,700
Custody sergeants don't really like to be hurried, do they?

399
00:28:27,700 --> 00:28:29,940
Just formalities. Fingerprints,

400
00:28:29,940 --> 00:28:32,750
charge sheet, and I've got to be in Magistrates' Court on Tuesday.

401
00:28:32,750 --> 00:28:36,700
- What? - Me, Sherlock! In court, on Tuesday!

402
00:28:36,700 --> 00:28:39,180
- They're giving me an ASBO! - Good, fine.

403
00:28:39,180 --> 00:28:41,820
You want to tell your little pal, he's welcome to go and own up any time.

404
00:28:41,820 --> 00:28:44,390
This symbol, I still can't place it.

405
00:28:44,870 --> 00:28:46,620
No, I need you to go to the police station

406
00:28:46,620 --> 00:28:48,050
and ask about the journalist.

407
00:28:48,050 --> 00:28:49,690
The personal effects will have been impounded.

408
00:28:49,690 --> 00:28:52,470
Get hold of his diary, or something that will tell us his movements.

409
00:28:53,890 --> 00:28:55,110
Go and see Van Coon's PA.

410
00:28:55,110 --> 00:28:58,310
If you retrace their steps, somewhere they'll coincide.

411
00:29:07,100 --> 00:29:08,320
Scotland Yard.

412
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:20,820
Flew back from Dalian Friday.

413
00:29:20,820 --> 00:29:23,490
Looks like he had back-to-back meetings with the sales team.

414
00:29:23,490 --> 00:29:24,970
Can you print me up a copy?

415
00:29:24,970 --> 00:29:27,270
- Sure. - What about the day he died?

416
00:29:27,270 --> 00:29:28,810
Can you tell me where he was?

417
00:29:28,810 --> 00:29:30,380
Sorry, I've got a gap.

418
00:29:31,650 --> 00:29:33,410
I have all his receipts.

419
00:29:33,410 --> 00:29:36,080
- Your friend... - Listen, whatever you say,

420
00:29:36,080 --> 00:29:38,100
I'm behind you 100 per cent.

421
00:29:38,100 --> 00:29:39,610
...he's an arrogant sod.

422
00:29:40,650 --> 00:29:43,760
Well, that was mild. People say a lot worse than that.

423
00:29:45,550 --> 00:29:48,180
This is what you wanted, isn't it? The journalist's diary?

424
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:53,980


425
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:53,980


426
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:53,980


427
00:29:54,510 --> 00:29:57,400
What kind of a boss was he, Amanda? Appreciative?

428
00:29:57,400 --> 00:30:00,360
Um, no. That's not a word I'd use.

429
00:30:00,360 --> 00:30:04,600
The only things Eddie appreciated had a big price tag.

430
00:30:04,600 --> 00:30:07,670
Like that hand cream. He bought that for you, didn't he?

431
00:30:13,060 --> 00:30:14,890
Look at this one.

432
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:18,170


433
00:30:18,170 --> 00:30:19,790
That would get him to the office.

434
00:30:19,790 --> 00:30:22,480
Not rush hour. Check the time. Mid-morning. 18 would get him

435
00:30:22,480 --> 00:30:25,310
- as far as... - ..The West End. I remember him saying.

436
00:30:26,870 --> 00:30:28,610
Underground, printed at one in Piccadilly.

437
00:30:28,610 --> 00:30:31,230
So he got a Tube back to the office.

438
00:30:31,890 --> 00:30:34,640
Why would he get a taxi into town, and then the Tube back?

439
00:30:34,640 --> 00:30:36,750
Because he was delivering something heavy.

440
00:30:36,750 --> 00:30:38,660
You wouldn't lug a package up the escalator.

441
00:30:38,660 --> 00:30:40,290
Delivering?!

442
00:30:40,290 --> 00:30:42,020
To somewhere near Piccadilly Station.

443
00:30:42,020 --> 00:30:44,690
Dropped the package, delivered it, and then...

444
00:30:46,790 --> 00:30:49,640
Stopped on his way. He got peckish.

445
00:30:46,020 --> 00:30:47,380


446
00:30:47,460 --> 00:30:48,220


447
00:30:52,850 --> 00:30:56,460
So you bought your lunch from here en route to the station

448
00:30:56,460 --> 00:30:57,350
but where were you headed from?

449
00:30:57,350 --> 00:30:59,930
Where did the taxi drop you?

450
00:30:59,930 --> 00:31:01,260
Oof! Right.

451
00:31:01,260 --> 00:31:03,980
Eddie Van Coon brought a package here the day he died.

452
00:31:03,980 --> 00:31:05,480
Whatever was hidden inside that case...

453
00:31:05,480 --> 00:31:06,620
I've managed to piece together a picture

454
00:31:06,720 --> 00:31:09,070
using scraps of information - credit card bills, receipts.

455
00:31:09,080 --> 00:31:11,660
- He flew back from China, then he came here.  - Sherlock.

456
00:31:11,660 --> 00:31:14,020
Somewhere in this street, somewhere near. I don't know where, but...

457
00:31:14,020 --> 00:31:16,260
That shop, over there.

458
00:31:16,260 --> 00:31:17,740
How could you tell?

459
00:31:17,740 --> 00:31:19,500
Lukis' diary. He was here too.

460
00:31:19,500 --> 00:31:20,800
He wrote down the address.

461
00:31:47,180 --> 00:31:48,700
Hello.

462
00:31:54,500 --> 00:31:57,140
You want... lucky cat?

463
00:31:57,140 --> 00:31:59,780
No, thanks, no.

464
00:31:59,780 --> 00:32:02,540


465
00:32:03,900 --> 00:32:06,820
I think your wife, she will like.

466
00:32:06,820 --> 00:32:08,820
Um, thank you.

467
00:32:17,680 --> 00:32:18,980
Sherlock...

468
00:32:20,820 --> 00:32:23,640
- The label there.  - Yes, I see it.

469
00:32:23,640 --> 00:32:24,740
It's exactly the same as the cipher.

470
00:32:30,720 --> 00:32:34,560
It's an ancient number system. Hang Zhou.

471
00:32:34,560 --> 00:32:36,920
These days only street traders use it.

472
00:32:36,920 --> 00:32:40,080
Those were numbers written on the wall at the bank and at the library.

473
00:32:40,080 --> 00:32:43,160
Numbers written in an ancient Chinese dialect.

474
00:32:43,160 --> 00:32:44,840
It's a 15.

475
00:32:44,840 --> 00:32:46,960
What we thought was the artist's tag, it's a number 15.

476
00:32:46,960 --> 00:32:50,920
And the blindfold, the horizontal line. That was a number as well.

477
00:32:50,920 --> 00:32:53,320
- The Chinese number one, John.  - We found it.

478
00:32:59,320 --> 00:33:02,240
Two men travel back from China,

479
00:33:02,240 --> 00:33:06,880
both head straight for the Lucky Cat emporium.

480
00:33:06,880 --> 00:33:09,080
What did they see?

481
00:33:09,080 --> 00:33:11,160
It's not what they saw.

482
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:14,520
It's what they both brought back in those suitcases.

483
00:33:14,520 --> 00:33:17,680
And you don't mean duty free.

484
00:33:17,680 --> 00:33:19,040
Thank you.

485
00:33:23,640 --> 00:33:25,440
Think about what Sebastian told us.

486
00:33:25,440 --> 00:33:28,160
About Van Coon, about how he stayed afloat in the market.

487
00:33:28,160 --> 00:33:31,080
- Lost 5 million.  - Made it back in a week.

488
00:33:31,080 --> 00:33:32,920
That's how he made such easy money.

489
00:33:32,920 --> 00:33:35,680
He was a smuggler. Mm.

490
00:33:35,680 --> 00:33:37,480
Cover would have been perfect.

491
00:33:39,040 --> 00:33:41,800
Businessman, making frequent trips to Asia.

492
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:45,000
Lukis was the same, a journalist writing about China.

493
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:47,440
Both of them smuggled stuff about.

494
00:33:47,440 --> 00:33:49,720
The Lucky Cat was their drop-off.

495
00:33:49,720 --> 00:33:51,880
But why did they die?

496
00:33:51,880 --> 00:33:53,310
It doesn't make sense.

497
00:33:53,310 --> 00:33:55,560
If they both turn up at the shop and deliver the goods,

498
00:33:55,560 --> 00:33:57,240
why would someone threaten them

499
00:33:57,240 --> 00:34:00,480
and kill them after the event, after they'd finished the job?

500
00:34:04,800 --> 00:34:06,600
What if one of them was light-fingered?

501
00:34:06,600 --> 00:34:08,560
- How do you mean?  - Stole something.

502
00:34:08,560 --> 00:34:10,080
Something from the hoard.

503
00:34:10,080 --> 00:34:12,080
The killer doesn't know which of them took it

504
00:34:12,080 --> 00:34:13,560
so threatens them both. Right.

505
00:34:16,200 --> 00:34:18,160
Remind me.

506
00:34:18,160 --> 00:34:20,760
When was the last time that it rained?

507
00:34:25,220 --> 00:34:26,540


508
00:34:29,760 --> 00:34:31,600
It's been here since Monday.

509
00:34:34,740 --> 00:34:35,500


510
00:34:43,080 --> 00:34:46,360
No-one's been in that flat for at least three days.

511
00:34:46,360 --> 00:34:48,400
Could have gone on holiday.

512
00:34:48,400 --> 00:34:51,200
Do you leave your windows open when you go on holiday?

513
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:03,960
Sherlock!

514
00:35:09,520 --> 00:35:12,280
Someone else has been here.

515
00:35:12,280 --> 00:35:15,730
Somebody else broke into the flat and knocked over the vase,

516
00:35:15,730 --> 00:35:17,320
just like I did.

517
00:35:27,920 --> 00:35:29,960
Do you think maybe you could let me in this time?

518
00:35:34,640 --> 00:35:37,160
Can you not keep doing this, please?

519
00:35:43,600 --> 00:35:45,320
I'm not the first.

520
00:35:47,240 --> 00:35:50,360
- What?  - Somebody's been in here before me.

521
00:35:51,400 --> 00:35:52,960
What are you saying?

522
00:35:55,480 --> 00:35:58,480
Size eight feet.

523
00:35:58,480 --> 00:36:03,240
Small, but...athletic.

524
00:36:03,240 --> 00:36:05,040
I'm wasting my breath.

525
00:36:08,880 --> 00:36:12,040
Small, strong hands.

526
00:36:14,360 --> 00:36:15,880
Our acrobat.

527
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:19,800
Why didn't he close the window when he lef...?

528
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:22,720
Oh, stupid, stupid!

529
00:36:22,720 --> 00:36:24,720
Obvious.

530
00:36:24,720 --> 00:36:26,320
He's still here.

531
00:36:48,880 --> 00:36:51,960
Any time you want to include me...

532
00:36:51,960 --> 00:36:53,760
John...

533
00:36:53,760 --> 00:36:55,880
John!

534
00:36:57,600 --> 00:36:59,600
Oh, I'm Sherlock Holmes and I always work alone

535
00:36:59,600 --> 00:37:02,600
because no-one else can compete with my massive intellect!

536
00:37:45,120 --> 00:37:47,320
The milk's gone off and the washing's started to smell.

537
00:37:47,320 --> 00:37:50,200
- Somebody left here in a hurry three days ago.  - Somebody?

538
00:37:50,800 --> 00:37:53,920
Soo Lin Yao. We have to find her.

539
00:37:53,920 --> 00:37:55,640
How, exactly?

540
00:37:55,940 --> 00:37:58,640


541
00:37:58,740 --> 00:38:00,240


542
00:38:00,400 --> 00:38:01,720
We could start with this.

543
00:38:01,720 --> 00:38:04,720
You've gone all croaky. Are you getting a cold?

544
00:38:04,720 --> 00:38:06,360
I'm fine.

545
00:38:07,680 --> 00:38:10,080
When was the last time that you saw her?

546
00:38:10,080 --> 00:38:12,600
Three days ago. Here at the museum.

547
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:16,560
This morning they told me she'd resigned.

548
00:38:16,560 --> 00:38:20,120
Just like that. Left her work unfinished.

549
00:38:20,120 --> 00:38:24,000
What was the last thing that she did on her final afternoon?

550
00:38:27,640 --> 00:38:33,320
She does this demonstration for the tourists, a tea ceremony.

551
00:38:33,320 --> 00:38:37,920
So she would have packed up her things and just put them in here.

552
00:38:56,160 --> 00:38:58,120
We have to get to Soo Lin Yao.

553
00:38:58,120 --> 00:39:00,440
- If she's still alive.  - Sherlock!

554
00:39:00,440 --> 00:39:03,080
Oh, look who it is.

555
00:39:03,080 --> 00:39:04,520
Found something you'll like.

556
00:39:10,880 --> 00:39:12,880
Tuesday morning,

557
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:15,000
all you've got to do is turn up and say the bag was yours.

558
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:16,600
Forget about your court date.

559
00:39:22,080 --> 00:39:24,120
Dude, that was rad!

560
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:28,600
You want to hide a tree, then a forest is the best place to do it,

561
00:39:28,600 --> 00:39:30,280
wouldn't you say?

562
00:39:30,280 --> 00:39:32,960
People would just walk straight past, not knowing,

563
00:39:32,960 --> 00:39:34,760
unable to decipher the message.

564
00:39:36,760 --> 00:39:39,040
There. I spotted it earlier.

565
00:39:40,640 --> 00:39:42,920
They've been here. And that's the exact same paint?

566
00:39:42,920 --> 00:39:43,920
Yeah.

567
00:39:43,920 --> 00:39:46,160
John, if we're going to decipher this code,

568
00:39:46,160 --> 00:39:47,840
we need to look for more evidence.

569
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:51,720
Answer your phone. I've been calling you.

570
00:40:51,720 --> 00:40:54,480
I found it.

571
00:41:08,600 --> 00:41:10,240
It's been painted over.

572
00:41:13,640 --> 00:41:17,080
I don't understand. It was... here.

573
00:41:18,760 --> 00:41:20,640
10 minutes ago. I saw it.

574
00:41:20,640 --> 00:41:22,400
A whole load of graffiti.

575
00:41:22,400 --> 00:41:24,480
Somebody doesn't want me to see it.

576
00:41:25,880 --> 00:41:28,760
- Sherlock, what are you doing...?  - Ssh! John, concentrate.

577
00:41:28,760 --> 00:41:30,600
I need you to concentrate. Close your eyes.

578
00:41:30,600 --> 00:41:33,120
What? Why? Why? What are you doing?

579
00:41:33,120 --> 00:41:35,800
I need you to maximise your visual memory.

580
00:41:35,800 --> 00:41:37,760
Try to picture what you saw.

581
00:41:37,760 --> 00:41:39,880
- Can you picture it?  - Yeah.

582
00:41:39,880 --> 00:41:41,640
- Can you remember it?  - Yes, definitely.

583
00:41:41,640 --> 00:41:42,720
Can you remember the pattern?

584
00:41:42,720 --> 00:41:44,440
- Yes.  - How much can you remember it?

585
00:41:44,440 --> 00:41:45,600
Look, don't worry.

586
00:41:45,600 --> 00:41:49,040
Because the average human memory on visual matters is only 62% accurate.

587
00:41:49,040 --> 00:41:51,320
- Well, don't worry, I remember all of it.  - Really?

588
00:41:51,320 --> 00:41:55,760
At least I would, if I could get to my pockets. I took a photograph.

589
00:42:16,480 --> 00:42:18,760
Always in pairs, John, look.

590
00:42:20,440 --> 00:42:21,480
Numbers...

591
00:42:21,480 --> 00:42:23,360
come with partners.

592
00:42:23,360 --> 00:42:24,760
God, I need to sleep.

593
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:28,080
- Why did he paint it so near the tracks? - No idea.

594
00:42:28,080 --> 00:42:30,160
Thousands of people pass by there every day.

595
00:42:30,160 --> 00:42:32,160
Just 20 minutes...

596
00:42:33,320 --> 00:42:35,160
Of course.

597
00:42:35,160 --> 00:42:37,480
Of course, he wants information. He's trying to communicate

598
00:42:37,480 --> 00:42:39,600
with his people in the underworld.

599
00:42:39,600 --> 00:42:41,720
Whatever was stolen, he wants it back.

600
00:42:41,720 --> 00:42:45,360
It's somewhere here, in a code.

601
00:42:45,360 --> 00:42:48,640
We can't crack this without Soo Lin Yao.

602
00:42:48,640 --> 00:42:50,600
Oh, good.

603
00:42:50,600 --> 00:42:53,360
Two men who travelled back from China were murdered.

604
00:42:53,360 --> 00:42:56,480
And their killer left them messages in Hang Zhou numerals.

605
00:42:56,480 --> 00:42:58,480
Soo Lin Yao is in danger.

606
00:42:58,480 --> 00:43:01,360
That cipher, it was just the same pattern as the others.

607
00:43:01,360 --> 00:43:03,120
He means to kill her as well.

608
00:43:03,120 --> 00:43:05,040
Look, I've tried everywhere -

609
00:43:05,040 --> 00:43:07,640
friends, colleagues. I don't know where she's gone.

610
00:43:07,640 --> 00:43:09,960
I mean, she could be a thousand miles away.

611
00:43:11,600 --> 00:43:15,120
- What are you looking at? - Tell me more about those teapots.

612
00:43:15,120 --> 00:43:19,640
The pots were her obsession. They need urgent work.

613
00:43:19,640 --> 00:43:22,000
If they dry out, then the clay can start to crumble.

614
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:25,120
Apparently, you have to just keep making tea in them.

615
00:43:25,120 --> 00:43:28,960
Yesterday, only one of those pots was shining.

616
00:43:28,960 --> 00:43:30,680
Now, there are two.

617
00:44:20,840 --> 00:44:23,800
Fancy a biscuit with that?

618
00:44:25,640 --> 00:44:28,800
Centuries old. Don't want to break that.

619
00:44:35,360 --> 00:44:37,320
Hello.

620
00:44:37,320 --> 00:44:39,120
You saw the cipher.

621
00:44:39,120 --> 00:44:42,720
Then you know he is coming for me.

622
00:44:42,720 --> 00:44:46,280
You've been clever to avoid him so far.

623
00:44:46,280 --> 00:44:48,520
I had to finish.

624
00:44:48,520 --> 00:44:50,400
To finish this work.

625
00:44:52,280 --> 00:44:54,480
It's only a matter of time.

626
00:44:54,480 --> 00:44:57,040
I know he will find me.

627
00:44:57,040 --> 00:44:59,960
Who is he? Have you met him before?

628
00:45:01,480 --> 00:45:05,040
When I was a girl, we met in China.

629
00:45:06,880 --> 00:45:09,480
I recognised his...

630
00:45:09,480 --> 00:45:11,840
- signature. - The cipher?

631
00:45:13,760 --> 00:45:18,040
Only he would do this. Zhi Zhu.

632
00:45:18,040 --> 00:45:21,600
- Zhi Zhu? - The spider.

633
00:45:26,840 --> 00:45:28,200
You know this mark?

634
00:45:28,200 --> 00:45:31,320
Yes. It's the mark of a Tong.

635
00:45:31,320 --> 00:45:35,920
- Huh? - Ancient crime syndicate, based in China.

636
00:45:38,280 --> 00:45:40,920
Every foot soldier bears the mark.

637
00:45:42,400 --> 00:45:44,240
Everyone who hauls for them.

638
00:45:44,240 --> 00:45:46,160
Hauls?

639
00:45:49,120 --> 00:45:50,680
You mean you were a smuggler?

640
00:45:54,760 --> 00:45:56,680
I was 15.

641
00:45:58,600 --> 00:46:00,280
My parents were dead.

642
00:46:01,400 --> 00:46:03,320
I had no livelihood.

643
00:46:04,120 --> 00:46:08,040
No way of surviving, day-to-day,

644
00:46:08,040 --> 00:46:10,040
except to work for the bosses.

645
00:46:10,040 --> 00:46:11,840
Who are they?

646
00:46:11,840 --> 00:46:15,880
They are called the Black Lotus.

647
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:21,240
By the time I was 16,

648
00:46:22,760 --> 00:46:26,400
I was taking thousands of pounds worth of drugs

649
00:46:26,400 --> 00:46:28,320
across the border into Hong Kong.

650
00:46:32,240 --> 00:46:35,200
I managed to leave that life behind me.

651
00:46:37,080 --> 00:46:39,000
I came to England.

652
00:46:40,640 --> 00:46:42,920
They gave me a job, here.

653
00:46:45,800 --> 00:46:49,760
Everything was good. New life.

654
00:46:49,760 --> 00:46:52,560
And he came looking for you.

655
00:46:52,560 --> 00:46:54,040
Yes.

656
00:46:56,520 --> 00:47:00,280
I hoped, after five years...

657
00:47:00,280 --> 00:47:02,400
maybe they would have forgotten me.

658
00:47:03,680 --> 00:47:06,280
But they never really let you leave.

659
00:47:08,680 --> 00:47:10,880
A small community like ours...

660
00:47:12,400 --> 00:47:14,400
..they are never very far away.

661
00:47:20,600 --> 00:47:22,480
He came to my flat.

662
00:47:22,480 --> 00:47:27,120
He asked me to help him to track down something that was stolen.

663
00:47:27,120 --> 00:47:29,040
And you've no idea what it was?

664
00:47:29,040 --> 00:47:31,320
I refused to help.

665
00:47:31,320 --> 00:47:35,640
So, you knew him well when you were living back in China?

666
00:47:37,560 --> 00:47:39,400
Oh, yes.

667
00:47:41,080 --> 00:47:43,040
He's my brother.

668
00:47:56,480 --> 00:47:59,200
Two orphans.

669
00:48:00,920 --> 00:48:03,080
We had no choice.

670
00:48:05,080 --> 00:48:07,760
We could work for the Black Lotus,

671
00:48:07,760 --> 00:48:10,440
or starve on the streets, like beggars.

672
00:48:14,920 --> 00:48:17,560
My brother has become their puppet.

673
00:48:18,800 --> 00:48:23,240
In the power of the one they call Shan.

674
00:48:23,240 --> 00:48:25,000
The Black Lotus general.

675
00:48:28,360 --> 00:48:30,640
I turned my brother away.

676
00:48:32,920 --> 00:48:35,360
He said I had betrayed him.

677
00:48:37,920 --> 00:48:40,320
Next day, I came to work

678
00:48:40,320 --> 00:48:42,720
and the cipher was waiting.

679
00:48:49,080 --> 00:48:50,920
Can you decipher these?

680
00:48:52,680 --> 00:48:55,360
- These are numbers. - Yes, I know.

681
00:48:55,360 --> 00:49:00,680
Here, the line across the man's eyes, it's the Chinese number one.

682
00:49:00,680 --> 00:49:03,440
And this one is 15. But what's the code?

683
00:49:04,560 --> 00:49:07,000
All the smugglers know it.

684
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:08,680
It's based upon a book...

685
00:49:13,640 --> 00:49:15,160
He's here.

686
00:49:16,200 --> 00:49:19,680
Zhi Zhu has found me.

687
00:49:19,680 --> 00:49:21,960
No, no, Sherlock.

688
00:49:21,960 --> 00:49:23,000
Sherlock, wait!

689
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:24,840
Come here.

690
00:49:24,840 --> 00:49:26,800
Get in. Get in!

691
00:49:42,440 --> 00:49:45,160
I have to go and help him. Bolt the door after me.

692
00:50:16,880 --> 00:50:19,040
Careful!

693
00:50:19,040 --> 00:50:23,400
Some of those skulls are over 200,000 years old. Have a bit of respect.

694
00:50:26,280 --> 00:50:28,240
Thank you.

695
00:51:25,720 --> 00:51:27,240
Liang.

696
00:51:28,760 --> 00:51:31,160


697
00:51:34,480 --> 00:51:37,280


698
00:51:43,360 --> 00:51:44,880
Oh, my God.

699
00:52:17,320 --> 00:52:18,960
How many murders is it going to take

700
00:52:18,960 --> 00:52:21,680
before you start believing that this maniac's out there?

701
00:52:23,400 --> 00:52:25,800
A young girl was gunned down tonight.

702
00:52:25,800 --> 00:52:29,640
That's three victims in three days. You're supposed to be finding him.

703
00:52:29,640 --> 00:52:31,000
Brian Lukis and Eddie Van Coon

704
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:33,360
were working for a gang of international smugglers.

705
00:52:33,360 --> 00:52:36,920
A gang called the Black Lotus, operating here in London

706
00:52:36,920 --> 00:52:39,160
right under your nose.

707
00:52:39,160 --> 00:52:40,560
Can you prove that?

708
00:52:48,520 --> 00:52:51,160
- What are you thinking? Pork or pasta? - Oh, it's you.

709
00:52:52,160 --> 00:52:55,200
I suppose it's never going to trouble Egon Ronay, is it?

710
00:52:55,200 --> 00:52:56,760
I'd stick with the pasta.

711
00:52:56,760 --> 00:53:01,040
Don't want to be doing roast pork, not if you're slicing up cadavers.

712
00:53:01,040 --> 00:53:03,400
What are you having?

713
00:53:03,400 --> 00:53:05,840
I don't eat when I'm working. Digesting slows me down.

714
00:53:05,840 --> 00:53:08,720
So you're working here tonight?

715
00:53:08,720 --> 00:53:10,560
- Need to examine some bodies. - Some?

716
00:53:10,560 --> 00:53:13,360
Eddie Van Coon and Brian Lukis.

717
00:53:13,360 --> 00:53:14,920
They're on my list.

718
00:53:16,480 --> 00:53:18,800
Could you wheel them out again for me?

719
00:53:18,800 --> 00:53:23,040
Well...their paperwork's already gone through.

720
00:53:26,640 --> 00:53:29,800
- You changed your hair. - What?

721
00:53:29,800 --> 00:53:32,400
The style. It's usually parted in the middle.

722
00:53:32,400 --> 00:53:34,000
Yes, well...

723
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:35,240
It's good.

724
00:53:35,240 --> 00:53:37,640
It...suits you better this way.

725
00:53:48,560 --> 00:53:50,360
We're just interested in the feet.

726
00:53:50,360 --> 00:53:52,160
- The feet? - Yes.

727
00:53:52,160 --> 00:53:53,960
Do you mind if we have a look at them?

728
00:54:01,680 --> 00:54:03,320
Now, Van Coon.

729
00:54:09,200 --> 00:54:12,640
- Oh! - So...

730
00:54:12,640 --> 00:54:15,960
So either these two men just happened to visit the same Chinese tattoo Parlour,

731
00:54:16,020 --> 00:54:19,070
- Or I'm telling the truth. - What do you want?

732
00:54:19,070 --> 00:54:21,590
I want every book from Lukis' apartment and Van Coon's.

733
00:54:21,590 --> 00:54:23,830
Their books?

734
00:54:27,110 --> 00:54:30,750
Not just a criminal organisation. It's a cult.

735
00:54:32,910 --> 00:54:35,230
Her brother was corrupted by one of its leaders.

736
00:54:35,710 --> 00:54:36,670
Soo Lin said the name.

737
00:54:36,670 --> 00:54:39,430
Yes, Shan. General Shan.

738
00:54:39,430 --> 00:54:41,110
We're still no closer to finding him.

739
00:54:41,110 --> 00:54:43,430
Wrong! We've got almost all we need to know.

740
00:54:43,430 --> 00:54:46,510
She gave us most of the missing pieces.

741
00:54:47,930 --> 00:54:49,110
Why did he need to visit his sister?

742
00:54:49,110 --> 00:54:50,610
Why did he need her expertise?

743
00:54:50,610 --> 00:54:51,670
She worked at the museum.

744
00:54:51,670 --> 00:54:53,870
- Exactly. - An expert in antiquities.

745
00:54:55,150 --> 00:54:55,820
Of course, I see.

746
00:54:55,820 --> 00:54:57,430
Valuable antiquities, John.

747
00:54:57,430 --> 00:55:00,270
Ancient Chinese relics purchased on the black market.

748
00:55:00,270 --> 00:55:03,510
China's home to a thousand treasures hidden after Mao's revolution.

749
00:55:03,510 --> 00:55:04,950
The Black Lotus is selling them.

750
00:55:07,950 --> 00:55:09,950


751
00:55:10,150 --> 00:55:12,470
Check for the dates...

752
00:55:12,470 --> 00:55:15,110
Here, John, "arrived from China four days ago".

753
00:55:15,990 --> 00:55:17,670
Anonymous.

754
00:55:17,670 --> 00:55:20,150
The vendor doesn't give his name.

755
00:55:20,150 --> 00:55:22,630
"Two undiscovered treasures from the East."

756
00:55:22,630 --> 00:55:25,040
One in Lukis' suitcase,

757
00:55:25,040 --> 00:55:27,150
...and one in Van Coon's.

758
00:55:27,150 --> 00:55:32,150
"Antiquities... sold at auction."

759
00:55:32,430 --> 00:55:34,790
Look, here's another one.

760
00:55:34,790 --> 00:55:36,040
Arrived from China a month ago,

761
00:55:36,040 --> 00:55:39,950
Chinese ceramic statue sold for 400,000 pounds.

762
00:55:39,950 --> 00:55:43,350
Look, a month before that, Chinese painting, 500,000 pounds.

763
00:55:43,350 --> 00:55:45,670
All of them from an anonymous source.

764
00:55:45,670 --> 00:55:48,060
They're stealing them back in China

765
00:55:48,060 --> 00:55:49,530
...and one by one feeding them into Britain.

766
00:55:52,990 --> 00:55:54,110
Every single auction

767
00:55:54,110 --> 00:55:57,590
coincides with Lukis or Van Coon travelling to China.

768
00:55:57,590 --> 00:55:59,230
So what if one of them got greedy when they were in China?

769
00:55:59,230 --> 00:56:00,790
What if one of them stole something?

770
00:56:00,790 --> 00:56:03,110
That's why Zhi Zhu's come.

771
00:56:03,110 --> 00:56:06,270
Sorry, are we collecting for charity, Sherlock?

772
00:56:06,270 --> 00:56:07,430
What?

773
00:56:07,430 --> 00:56:10,310
A young man's outside with crates of books.

774
00:56:16,070 --> 00:56:17,870
So the numbers are references.

775
00:56:17,870 --> 00:56:19,270
To books.

776
00:56:19,780 --> 00:56:22,670
To specific pages and specific words on those pages.

777
00:56:23,540 --> 00:56:27,070
Right, so... 15 and 1, that means?

778
00:56:27,070 --> 00:56:29,270
Turn to page 15 and it's the first word you read.

779
00:56:29,270 --> 00:56:30,420
OK, so what's the message?

780
00:56:30,420 --> 00:56:31,480
Depends on the book.

781
00:56:32,190 --> 00:56:34,590
That's the cunning of the book code.

782
00:56:34,590 --> 00:56:36,550
It has to be one that they both own.

783
00:56:40,230 --> 00:56:44,350
OK, fine. This shouldn't take too long, should it?

784
00:56:57,500 --> 00:57:01,110
We found these at the museum. Is this your writing?

785
00:57:01,110 --> 00:57:04,710
Er, we hoped Soo Lin could decipher it for us.

786
00:57:07,550 --> 00:57:09,230
Anything else I can do?

787
00:57:09,230 --> 00:57:11,390
To assist you, I mean.

788
00:57:11,390 --> 00:57:13,750
Some silence right now would be marvellous.

789
00:57:29,260 --> 00:57:30,780


790
00:57:28,430 --> 00:57:30,790
Cigarette.

791
00:57:58,510 --> 00:58:00,790
Imagine.

792
00:57:59,260 --> 00:58:00,820


793
00:58:20,670 --> 00:58:22,190
I'm sorry to keep you waiting,

794
00:58:22,190 --> 00:58:25,990
but we haven't got anything now until next Thursday.

795
00:58:25,990 --> 00:58:28,830
This is taking ages.

796
00:58:28,830 --> 00:58:30,190
